        output='Based on the provided S-1 registration statement and prospectus excerpts, here are the details of the dual-class share structure, voting rights, and ownership for Space Exploration Technologies Corp. (SpaceX):\n\n### **1. Share Classes & Voting Rights**\nThe company\'s common stock is divided into classes with disparate voting rights, designed to concentrate voting control among insiders and early investors.\n*   **Class A Common Stock:** Entitles the holder to **1 vote per share**. \n*   **Class B Common Stock:** Entitles the holder to **10 votes per share**.\n*   **General Voting:** On most standard corporate matters, Class A and Class B shareholders vote together as a single class.\n*   **Class C Common Stock:** (Mentioned for context) Carries **no voting rights**, except as required by law.\n\n### **2. Board Control & Special Protective Provisions**\nDespite voting together on most issues, the Class B shares possess exclusive "super-voting" rights regarding corporate control and governance:\n*   **Board of Directors:** Class B shareholders, voting separately as a class, have the exclusive right to elect **51% of the total authorized board of directors** (rounded up to the nearest whole number). The remaining directors ("Common Stock Directors") are elected by Class A and B shareholders voting together.\n*   **Elon Musk\'s Protective Rights:** The removal of Elon Musk from his board and leadership roles (CEO and Chairman) requires the approval of a majority of the voting power of the outstanding Class B shares, voting separately as a class.\n*   **Charter Amendments & Mergers:** Class B approval (voting separately) is required to amend the charter in any way that alters Class B rights/privileges, or to approve certain combinations, mergers, or sales of the company.\n\n### **3. Conversion Mechanics**\nTo prevent the permanent entrenchment of super-voting shares if they are sold to the public, the charter includes strict conversion rules:\n*   **Voluntary Conversion:** A Class B shareholder can convert their shares into Class A shares at any time on a **1-to-1 basis**.\n*   **Automatic Conversion:** Class B shares **automatically convert** into Class A shares (losing their 10x voting multiplier) upon any "Transfer" (sale or transfer of legal/beneficial interest). \n*   **Permitted Transfers:** The automatic conversion does *not* apply to "Permitted Transfers," which generally include transfers for estate planning purposes (e.g., to certain family trusts, inter-family transfers, or specific permitted entities).\n\n### **4. Who Holds Each Class?**\nThe dual-class structure heavily concentrates voting power in the hands of the founder and key insiders, leaving public IPO investors with limited influence.\n\n**Class B Holders (Insiders, Founders, and Early Investors):**\n*   **Elon Musk:** Post-IPO, Musk will beneficially own a **majority of the outstanding Class B shares** and a majority of the company\'s total voting power. He holds these shares directly, through trusts (e.g., the Mission Trust, EM 2024 GRAT-A), and via exercisable stock options. This guarantees his control over the board and his own employment/leadership status.\n*   **Gwynne Shotwell (President & COO):** Holds millions of Class B shares directly, alongside her Class A holdings.\n*   **Ira Ehrenpreis (Director):** Holds Class B shares (alongside Class A) through a revocable trust.\n*   **Initial Class B Directors:** Musk, Shotwell, Antonio J. Gracias, Donald Harrison, and Luke Nosek are slated to serve as the initial directors elected by the Class B shares.\n*   **xAI Merger Participants:** As part of a pre-IPO merger, holders of **xAI "High Vote" Preferred Stock** (Series A) had their shares converted into SpaceX Class B Common Stock.\n\n**Class A Holders (Public Investors, Employees, and Certain Insiders):**\n*   **Public IPO Investors:** The shares being offered in the Nasdaq IPO (under the ticker "SPCX") are exclusively Class A shares. These investors will have minimal influence over corporate governance or board elections.\n*   **Employees & Option Holders:** Stock options and RSUs granted under share-based compensation plans generally convert into or are settled in Class A shares.\n*   **Certain Insiders:** Executives like Bret Johnsen hold significant amounts of Class A stock and options. Elon Musk and Gwynne Shotwell also hold millions of Class A shares alongside their Class B holdings.\n*   **xAI Merger Participants:** Holders of **xAI "Low Vote" Preferred Stock** (Series A-1, B, C, D, and E) had their shares converted into SpaceX Class A Common Stock.',
