as CEO, CTO, and Chairman of the Board. Under the charter, he can *only* be removed from the board or his leadership positions by an affirmative majority vote of the Class B shareholders.\n\n### **Controlled-Company Governance Exemptions**\nBecause it is a "controlled company," SpaceX intends to rely on exemptions to bypass several standard Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas corporate governance requirements. Specifically, the company **will not be required** to:\n1. **Maintain a Majority-Independent Board:** A majority of the board of directors does not need to consist of independent directors.\n2. **Use an Independent Nominating Committee:** Director nominees do not need to be selected or recommended by a nominating committee composed *entirely* of independent directors, nor does the committee need a written charter addressing the standard nominations process.\n3. **Use an Independent Compensation Committee:** The compensation committee does not need to be composed *entirely* of independent directors, nor does it need a written charter addressing all standard committee purposes and responsibilities.\n4. **Conduct Annual Evaluations:** The company is exempt from conducting annual performance evaluations of its compensation and nominating committees.\n\n*(Note: Despite these exemptions, the company remains subject to rules requiring its **audit committee** to be composed entirely of independent directors.)*\n\n### **Impact on Shareholders and Committee Composition**\n* **Reduced Protections:** The prospectus explicitly warns Class A shareholders that they will not have the same corporate governance protections afforded to shareholders of non-controlled companies. \n* **Committee Makeup:** Relying on the exemption, the post-IPO compensation and nominating committee will consist of Ira Ehrenpreis, Antonio J. Gracias, and Luke Nosek. While Ehrenpreis and Nosek qualify as independent, the exemption allows the company to include non-independent members and avoid adopting a fully compliant committee charter.\n* **Future Compliance:** If the company ever ceases to be a "controlled company" (e.g., if Musk\'s voting power drops below 50% or Class B shares are converted/sold), it will be required to comply with all standard Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas governance requirements within applicable transition periods.',
