        output='Based on the provided text, the corporate governance structure is heavily defined by a dual-class stock system that concentrates voting power and board control in the hands of Class B shareholders, specifically founder Elon Musk. \n\nHere are the detailed mechanics regarding board elections, director nominations, voting power, and the special rights of controlling stockholders:\n\n### 1. Voting Power & Dual-Class Structure\n*   **Class A Common Stock:** Entitled to **1 vote** per share.\n*   **Class B Common Stock:** Entitled to **10 votes** per share.\n*   **Class C Common Stock:** No voting rights.\n*   **General Voting:** Generally, Class A and Class B shareholders vote together as a single class. However, the charter grants Class B shareholders exclusive, separate class voting rights for specific critical matters, most notably board elections.\n*   **Conversion Mechanics:** Class B shares automatically convert into Class A shares (losing their 10x voting power) upon transfer, except for "Permitted Transfers" (e.g., certain inter-family or entity transfers). This mechanism increases the relative voting power over time for those who retain their Class B shares.\n\n### 2. Board Election Mechanics\nThe board is subject to **annual elections** (directors serve one-year terms until the next annual meeting), and **cumulative voting is not permitted**. The election of directors is split into two distinct tracks:\n*   **Class B Directors (Majority Control):** Holders of Class B common stock, voting separately as a class, have the exclusive right to elect **51% of the total authorized directors** (rounded up to the nearest whole number). This right persists for as long as any Class B shares remain outstanding.\n*   **Common Stock Directors:** Holders of all voting common stock (Class A and Class B combined), voting together as a single class, elect the remaining directors.\n*   **Initial Board Composition:** The initial post-IPO board will consist of 8 directors. \n    *   *Class B Directors:* Elon Musk, Gwynne Shotwell, Antonio J. Gracias, Donald Harrison, and Luke Nosek.\n    *   *Common Stock Directors:* Ira Ehrenpreis, Randy Glein, and Steve Jurvetson.\n\n### 3. Removal and Vacancy Filling\nThe power to remove directors and fill vacancies is strictly siloed based on how the director was elected:\n*   **Class B Directors:** May be removed with or without cause *only* by a majority vote of Class B shares (voting separately). Vacancies (including newly created seats) can *only* be filled by a majority vote of Class B shares or by the remaining Class B Directors.\n*   **Common Stock Directors:** May be removed with or without cause by a majority vote of all voting common stock (single class). Vacancies can be filled by a majority vote of all voting common stock or by the remaining directors.\n\n### 4. Director Nomination Rights & Advance Notice\n*   **Advance Notice Bylaws:** The bylaws establish advance notice procedures that shareholders must follow to properly bring director nominations or proposals before a meeting.\n*   **Controlling Stockholder Exemption:** **Elon Musk and his permitted transferees are explicitly exempt** from these advance notice procedures.\n*   **Nominating Committee Exemption:** Because the company qualifies as a "controlled company" under Nasdaq rules, it will rely on governance exemptions. Therefore, it is **not required** to have director nominees selected or recommended by a nominating committee composed entirely of independent directors.\n\n### 5. Special Rights of Controlling Stockholders (Elon Musk & Class B)\nPost-IPO, Elon Musk will hold a majority of the Class B shares and a majority of the combined voting power, granting him and Class B holders several entrenched protections and anti-takeover advantages:\n*   **Protected Leadership Roles:** Elon Musk can **only** be removed from the board, or from his roles as CEO and Chairman, with the affirmative approval of a majority of the voting power of Class B shares (voting separately as a class).\n*   **Absolute Board Control:** Because Musk controls the Class B vote (electing 51% of the board) and the combined voting majority (electing the remaining 49%), he effectively has the power to elect, remove, or fill vacancies for *all* directors.\n*   **Veto Power over Mergers & Charter Amendments:** Class B approval (voting separately) is strictly required to approve any charter amendment that alters Class B rights/privileges, as well as certain corporate combinations, mergers, or sales.\n*   **Calling Special Meetings:** Special shareholder meetings can be called by the Chairman, CEO, President, the Board, the **Founder (Musk)**, or shareholders holding at least 50% of the voting stock.\n*   **Action by Written Consent:** Shareholders can take action without a formal meeting or prior notice via written consent, provided they hold the minimum number of votes required to authorize the action (this applies to both the single-class vote and Class B separate-class votes).\n*   **Anti-Takeover Defenses:** The concentration of voting power, the prohibition of cumulative voting, the high threshold (50%) required for shareholders to call special meetings, and Texas anti-takeover statutes (TBOC Section 21.606) are explicitly noted to have the effect of deferring, delaying, or discouraging hostile takeovers or changes in management.',
