r relative to their economic stakes. \n\n*   **All Executive Officers and Directors (as a group):** \n    *   **Shares:** 1,402,027,270 Class A (20.2% of Class A) and 5,576,731,275 Class B (93.7% of Class B).\n    *   **Total Economic Interest:** ~55.7% of total outstanding shares.\n    *   **Voting Power:** 86.0% (heavily skewed by Musk\'s inclusion in this group).\n*   **Antonio J. Gracias (Director / 5% Shareholder):**\n    *   **Shares:** 503,414,530 Class A shares (7.3% of Class A) and 0 Class B shares.\n    *   **Total Economic Interest:** ~4.0% of total outstanding shares.\n    *   **Voting Power:** Less than 1% (*).\n*   **Luke Nosek (Director):**\n    *   **Shares:** 32,987,360 Class A shares.\n    *   **Total Economic Interest:** ~0.26%.\n*   **Bret Johnsen (Named Executive Officer):**\n    *   **Shares:** 9,583,690 Class A shares.\n    *   **Total Economic Interest:** ~0.07%.\n*   **Gwynne Shotwell (Named Executive Officer):**\n    *   **Shares:** 5,460,400 Class A and 7,113,550 Class B.\n    *   **Total Economic Interest:** ~0.10%.\n*   **Other Directors/Officers (Ira Ehrenpreis, Randy Glein, Donald Harrison, Steve Jurvetson):** Hold minor amounts of Class A and/or Class B shares, each representing less than 1% of their respective classes and total economic interest.\n\n### 3. Key Implications of this Ownership Structure\n*   **"Controlled Company" Status:** Because Musk holds greater than 50% of the voting power and Class B holders are entitled to elect 51% of the authorized directors, the company will be classified as a "controlled company" under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas rules.\n*   **Governance Exemptions:** As a controlled company, SpaceX is exempt from standard corporate governance requirements, such as having a majority of independent directors on the board, or requiring independent nominating and compensation committees.\n*   **Anti-Takeover Protections:** Musk\'s Class B shares allow him to elect, remove, or fill vacancies among "Class B Directors