    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided prospectus excerpts, the risk factors related to the company\'s "controlled company" status and dual-class stock structure heavily favor Elon Musk and Class B shareholders, leaving Class A public investors with significant governance and economic risks. \n\nHere is a breakdown of the specific risk factors and how they limit Class A shareholders\' rights:\n\n### 1. Risks of the Dual-Class Stock Structure\n*   **Disproportionate Voting Power:** Class A common stock is entitled to only **one vote per share**, while Class B common stock holds **10 votes per share**. Class A and Class B shareholders vote together as a single class on most matters, meaning Class B holders will easily dominate general shareholder votes.\n*   **Absolute Control Over the Board:** Holders of Class B common stock, voting separately as a class, have the exclusive right to elect **51% of the total authorized directors** (the "Class B Directors"). They also hold the sole power to remove these directors (with or without cause) and fill any vacancies. Because Elon Musk will own a majority of the Class B shares, he will unilaterally control the composition of the board.\n*   **Conversion Mechanics and Future Control Shifts:** Class B shares automatically convert to Class A shares upon transfer (with limited exceptions for permitted transferees). Over time, this increases the relative voting power of those who retain their Class B shares (like Mr. Musk). However, if Mr. Musk were to sell enough Class B shares to lose his majority, a new, unknown third party could gain control of the board and alter the company\'s strategic direction in ways that conflict with Class A shareholders\' interests.\n\n### 2. Risks of "Controlled Company" Status\nBecause Elon Musk will hold a majority of the voting power post-IPO, the company will qualify as a **"controlled company"** under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas rules. This allows the company to bypass standard corporate governance protections, including:\n*   **No Independent Board Majority:** The company is not required to have a majority of independent directors.\n*   **No Independent Nominating or Compensation Committees:** The company is exempt from requiring that director nominees be selected by an independent nominating committee, or that executive compensation be determined by an independent compensation committee. \n*   **No Annual Evaluations:** The company does not have to conduct annual performance evaluations of its nominating and compensation committees.\n*(Note: The company is still required to maintain an audit committee composed entirely of independent directors).*\n\n### 3. Limited Governance Rights for Class A Shareholders (Despite Economic Ownership)\nDespite bearing the economic risks of the company\'s performance and stock price volatility, Class A shareholders are effectively stripped of the governance rights typically associated with equity ownership:\n*   **Precluded Influence on Corporate Matters:** The concentration of voting power explicitly "limits or precludes" Class A shareholders from influencing corporate matters, electing directors, or forcing changes in management. Class A investors have no mechanism to hold the board accountable or vote out underperforming directors.\n*   **Waiver of Statutory Protections (TBOC Opt-Outs):** Under the Texas Business Organizations Code (TBOC), shareholders typically have the right to separate class votes on fundamental corporate changes (e.g., increasing/decreasing authorized shares, reclassifications, or exchanges of stock). The company\'s charter explicitly **opts out** of these TBOC protections. Consequently, Class A shareholders can be forced through major structural changes without their separate consent, as Class B\'s voting dominance will dictate the outcome.\n*   **Anti-Takeover Effects:** The dual-class structure and Musk\'s entrenched control act as a severe anti-takeover mechanism. Class A shareholders cannot initiate